[2
Date: Ven, 20 Nov 98 09:47:14 +0200
From: Marie Cornu <cornu@biomserv.univ-lyon1.fr>

To answer to the question asked by Aldert A Bergwerff about theoretical
risks associated with xenotransplantation, I'd want to make clear something
which was not mentioned in this message (as far as I understood it).
To my knowledge, it was never thought that pigs from usual farms could be
donors. There are special breedings in sterile conditions for that special
application (one already exists in western France and there may be many
others)
Only gnotobiotic (or axenic) pigs, which would have grown in perfectly
sterile conditions, could be candidate for xenotransplantation. So, the
risk of pathogens inhabiting pig's tissue would be therefore very limited,
as long as it concerns microorganisms.
On another point, as there would be special pig-breedings, in the special
aim to generate potential organ donors, all control tests (veterinary,
genetics...) could be carried out before or just after the animal is
killed. So
Of course, these risks have not to be neglected but I am led into thinking
that pigs would be "saner" donors than humans!
--
Marie CORNU
CNRS UMR 5558 Laboratoire de bacteriologie
