Date: Fri, 20 Nov 1998 15:25:51 -0800
From: Peter Smith <pjsmith1@gte.net>

In the moderators comments he stated that the question could be asked,
"Will pig be affected by human pathogens" in relation to the rising
discussion of pig pathogens infecting humans with transplanted organs. I do
not think that this really has any application, since the pig is not
receiving any organ from the human. If the pig was receiving transplants,
then maybe there is some type of discussion, but otherwise, this question
is not really applicable to the topic.
--
Peter Smith
Cal Poly Pomona
e-mail: pjsmith1@gte.net
[My suggestion was not totally tongue in cheek as the 'pig' is receiving an
organ ... the recipient human body and all it contains, including the blood
system keeping the pig organ going in its new home. Maybe transformations
can go on in both directions? Let us imagine, for the sake of theoretical
argument only, a pig farmer who receives a replacement kidney from a
gnotobiotic pig, recovers well, and one day while inspecting his healthy
pigs, he is taken short and pees in the pigshed ... Is he putting his pigs
at risk, the possible nature of that risk, and probabilistic size of it? I
suspect that the risk is trivial but my father taught me that one should
always ask the obvious questions as those are the ones folk don't ask. -
Martin Hugh-Jones, ProMED AHEAD moderator
