[4
Date: Fri, 20 Nov 1998 09:26:15 -0500
From: Alix Fano <afano@MA.NEAVS.COM>

I read Dr. Bergwerff's post on ProMED-mail about xenotransplantation. There
are several excellent reports and articles on the subject of viral risks
from pigs and primates that members of this list may wish to receive. If
anyone would like copies, please e-mail or send me your address and I will
forward them to you.
I am the spokesperson for the Campaign for Responsible Transplantation
(CRT), an international coalition of physicians, scientists, health care
professionals and laypersons representing over 2 million people around the
world, who oppose xenotransplantation because of the risks of transferring
animal viruses to humans. About 50 physicians, scientists, veterinarians
and lawyers have signed onto a legal petition that we are filing with the
U.S. Department of Health and Human Services to ban xenotransplants.
Last-minute signers are welcome, by December 1st.
There are numerous medical, scientific, medico-legal, economic,
environmental, and ethical problems associated with xenotransplantation.
For example, with 43 million Americans lacking basic healthcare, and 29
million underinsured in 1997, how can we justify resource allocation to
such an expensive technology. Screening one pig for (known) viruses will
cost $18,000. Nextran, breeder of transgenic pigs, acknowledges that animal
organs will cost as much as human organs. With the intensive monitoring,
follow-up care, immunosuppressive drug regimes, quarantine programs, and
lawsuits that may result from members of the public being involuntarily
exposed to animal viruses, these costs will likely soar. The U.S. Institute
of Medicine reported that xenotransplantation would increase annual
transplant costs from $3 billion to $20.3 billion. These are not small
considerations. Xenotransplantation's clinical track record is appalling,
with 100% of patients dying after receiving whole animal organs. Animal
experiments have also been disappointing, with most animals surviving 3
months with a xenograft. Moreover, animal experiments will not tell us how
an animal organ will function in a human.
In the U.S., the Environmental Protection Agency is clamping down on hog
breeding operations, as they have become an environmental hazard, dumping
billions of gallons of untreated manure into our nation's waterways,
killing fish and making people sick. Do we really need more pig facilities?
The answer, though it is not a profitable one, is to invest in disease
prevention. Last year the U.S. spent $425 billion treating the six leading
preventable chronic diseases, including heart disease, hypertension,
stroke, and liver disease. Studies have shown that low-fat vegetarian
diets, combined with exercise programs can prevent and reverse disease.
It is time we invest aggressively in these programs and stop meddling with
dangerous and unethical technologies that will place global human health at
risk, causing untold human and animal suffering.
--
Alix Fano
CRT
PO Box 120227
Boston, MA 02112-0227
e-mail: afano@MA.NEAVS.COM
[Some ground rules if this thread is to continue. Firstly, we limit
ourselves to the science, preferably hard science, of the subject and
ignore the other dimensions, however attractive, including the economic and
social opportunity costs of this research and development. Secondly, we
assume that the pigs to be used in these transplants are all very specially
bred and maintained gnotobiotic/axenic animals, and in due course that the
economics and availability will become attractive as in any profitable
industry. Thirdly, the original questions was and still is: "Should a
recipient, who is 'carrying' a foreign organ be afraid of microorganisms,
which are pathogenic to the donating animal?" - Mod.MHJ
